this topic may be easy for some,
I should start to explain what cut is.
Everyone here knows, that k4 cannot win,
because white will have the defensive four.
Such four can be called a "cut".
There is no official term for such element.
Some people call it a counter-four,
some people call it a block,
these two are not very clear expressions.
counter-four does not really describe the move k4,
when one player is attacing on one side,
and another player uses the attack on another side at the same time,
it can be called counter-four too
so, i do not like that expression, because it can have many meanings.
The word "cut" was invented by me long time ago.
the meaning of cut in my mind is,
when the opponent is attacking, and during the attack something comes up that cuts away his path of win,
then the player was been cut off,
and the atack failed because of the cut
so, the word 'cut' describes the move k5 so well,
it cuts the attempt of black win.
I also like the word cut because its so short and easy to use.
better to say cut than auto-defensive-four-or-three.
the cut may be a four, or a three,
but usually we mean a four,
in response to the opponents VCF attempt.
The image on the diagram shows the simplest cut.
It is simple, because the stones 12,10,8 were already present before black's offensive.
So it was easy to see the cut coming.
So, many of you think, if this is so simple, why need to learn it.
not all cuts are easy and obvious.
Is here anyone among you who never been trapped by a cut?? Is here anyone who always sees all cuts in games??
not, haha, but i give some to others. :)))
Some cuts are very hard to see,
especially when long VCF attack is used
then it is hard to see the stones coming up, creating a cut.
that we dont even notice it when the cut is already there, with 4 stones in a row.
game with Nikonov was one of them...
some of them is too complication
white was so happy with vcf,
that was about to bring 4x4 at d5,
they missed the cut at move 49
It has something to do with our brain.
Do you remember, Claire posted a message in forum, asking to count the F letters, and we all missed half of them
our brain sometimes doesnt get it
we are distracted by the joy of VCF we dound
and we lose tract and care of details
This has nothing to do with the skill.
Everyone knows the four is to be blocked.
I have played three serious tournament games in my life where I did not stop the four.
then I realized one thing that was in common:
all the cuts that I missed were diagonal fours
And this is my first conclusion:
people dont see diagonal cuts easily.
and the clock is running out of time,
we see the vertical or horisontal cut,
and we can see the "bigger are of same color"
Thats why we never miss the vertical or horisontal cut.
Our problem is, for example here,
the same reason why you did not see the "F" letters.
because we think they are irrelevant
Strong players who play in WC finals,
The difficulty of the cut is
the stones of the cut are not all there when the cut happens.
I will tell you the most famous story of the cut in renju history.
I am sorry. I will behave.
Some of you have heard it before in earlier lesson.
The team of Baltic-1 was the main favorite besides the Moscow-1.
I was the player in Baltic-1 team,
On the second table of our team,
there was a player from Lithuania,
we were going to play against St.Petersburg strong team.
Talsky's opponent was going to the Vladimir Semyonov.
They both were very interesting players.
Semyonov was the true fan of i3 opening,
and Talsky was the analyst of i3, searching all kinds of black wins in i3.
So, the master of i3 as black vs master of i3 as white.
Talsky had demonstrated many people his new ideas of i3,
this 7th move was Talsky's hot weapon,
and he was so proud of it.
Semyonov goes to Talsky before game, and proposes,
ok, I know you have your new win variant in i3,
and I let you play your 7th move,
The game began, Talsky played the first stone,
Talsky thought a bit before playing j8,
but he believed his opponent is a man of honor,
and he played i3, as agreed.
Semyonov was the man of honor, and didnt swap, as he had promised.
because nothing could stop from sure black win.
the news spread all along tournament hall,
people left their tables andcame to watch
Talsky knew that he had to play fast,
to show everyone that he had prepared well,
and accepted the duel from Semyonov in his favorite variant.
Talsky was fully enjoying the coming black win.
The big laugh filled the tournament hall
You know, usually, when the team-mate loses the game,
its a tragedy to the whole team,
and other team-mates are so sad,
all members of Baltic-1 team could not stop laughing
the famous variant of Talsky had died in a split second,
you can see, white is so strong
can you describe his face after the 24th move to us?
This story would not be so famous if it did not have the special background.
The deal the players made before game,
I guess Semenov was more happy than Talsky before the game :)
so move number 16 was the winning move
This cut happens to the greates players,
and it is missed often because of the huge amount of analysis the players make,
they do not have time to check all endings.
it so much lookes like black VCF
if similar cut NEVER happened to you before
you will most likely miss it too
Talsky got this poor loss because of this famous game,
but he was a great master,
he got 9.5 points from 11 on the second table of the team,
and helped Baltic-1 team to gold medal.

I analysed d3 long time ago,
It was after my match with Nakamura,
until then, active 10th moves had never been used before.
Move 10-j12 could be seen in Russian games
The move 9 is believed to be originated from Russia.
So, this was one of my first analyses about active 10th move,
but it was interesting in some aspects,
for example the use of cut.
but magic cut, do you see?
You have to think that white will try to be active,
and then you analyse possible VCF threats carefully.
Many players make the mistake here:
they assume 20 is VCF for white,
so they will give up move 19,
even if the opponent's VCF is obvious,
and then you can avoid mistakes that people do all the time in tournaments.
Some students made the mistake in 04/19 hw, too. CUT

One tactics of defense is just to block VCF,
another way is to cut it.
Here the cut is the best tactics.
Now, black is close to win,
but even strong players become careless in situation,
when there are more than one way to win.
Some play here, aiming for two 4x3s
so, black has to defend it.
The only option here is an artificial cut.
By this move, black solved three problems -
this move cuts the white VCF.
it blocks the overline danger at k11,
and it creates its own VCF threat,
I wanted to point out the artificial and natural cut here.
Natural cut is the line that just happens to be there,
and we do not need to do anything to make it effective.
Artificial cut is the line that we create just for cut purpose.
The moves 47 and 49 were artificial cuts.
Sometimes we are saved from the loss by "lucky" natural cut,
I am sure you all had such lucky cuts before,
you will learn more about making artificial cuts,
which give so much beauty to the game,
as the cuts are the most aggressive defense moves possible.
People love to see the gamres full of such cuts,
The cut is not just for traps,
it is a tactical tool of fighting,
we dont even need to "hide" it
Like the moves 47 and 49 are clear,
but important is that they are effective.
So, try to see the opportunities for artificial cuts in your games,
and beware of such cuts when the opponent is trying to make them for you
Its like beaty power shoots on goal from long distance are allways more atractive than low distance head-goals :))
Thank you all, the lesson ends here!
